---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Reviews from '../../components/Reviews.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/Hero.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import ImageFeature from '../../components/ImageFeature.astro';
import ScenarioHighlight from '../../components/ScenarioHighlight.astro';
import InsuranceBanner from '../../components/InsuranceBanner.astro';

const faqs = [
  { q: 'Do you offer addiction treatment in Korean?', a: 'Yes, Korean-language care, a rare offering in addiction treatment.' },
  { q: 'Is care in Korean genuine or just translation?', a: 'We provide real Korean-speaking care, not just a translation line.' },
  { q: 'Can my Korean-speaking family be involved?', a: 'Yes, we communicate with family and offer family therapy, with understanding of the cultural weight around addiction.' },
  { q: 'Do you treat mental health in Korean too?', a: 'Yes, co-occurring anxiety, depression, and trauma are treated alongside addiction.' },
  { q: 'Will my insurance cover it?', a: 'Most PPO plans do. As an out-of-network provider, we verify your benefits for free.' },
  { q: 'Where are you located?', a: 'In Burbank, serving the greater Los Angeles area including Koreatown and the Valley.' },
];
const faqSchema = { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: faqs.map((f) => ({ '@type': 'Question', name: f.q, acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a } })) };
const pageSchema = { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'MedicalWebPage', name: 'Korean-Speaking Detox & Rehab in Los Angeles', reviewedBy: { '@type': 'Person', name: 'Mileidys Gomez Gonzalez, MD' } };

const serves = [
  ['chat', 'Korean-speaking care', 'Treatment that meets you in your language, not translated around it.'],
  ['family', 'Culturally aware, family-run', 'A family-owned home that understands the role of family and the stigma many Korean clients carry.'],
  ['stethoscope', 'Whole-person, physician-led care', 'Two doctors on-site daily, treating addiction and the anxiety, depression, or trauma underneath.'],
  ['globe', 'Also in Spanish & English', 'Care is offered in English, Spanish, and Korean.'],
];
const GBP = 'https://maps.app.goo.gl/S3YvacbqJG8mVm457';
---
<Layout
  title="Korean-Speaking Detox & Rehab | Regain Hope Detox and Recovery Center"
  description="Korean-speaking detox and rehab in the Los Angeles area, real bilingual care, not just translation. A rare offering for Korean-speaking individuals and families. Call 24/7."
  schema={[pageSchema, faqSchema]}
>
  <Hero
    variant="form"
    eyebrow="한국어 지원 · Los Angeles · 24/7"
    title="Korean-Speaking Detox & Rehab in the Los Angeles Area"
    byline="Mileidys Gomez Gonzalez, MD"
    chips={['한국어 지원 · Korean-speaking care', 'Private & personal', 'Owned & run by two physicians', 'Close to LA\'s Korean community']}
  />

  <div class="trust"><div class="container">
    <span><span class="star">★</span> 5.0 on Google</span><span class="sep">|</span><span>Joint Commission Accredited</span><span class="sep">|</span><span>California DHCS Licensed</span><span class="sep">|</span><span>LegitScript Certified</span><span class="sep">|</span><span>Care in English & Korean</span>
  </div></div>

  <section><div class="container rich" style="max-width:820px;">
    <h2>Recovery is harder when no one speaks your language, or understands your culture</h2>
    <p>In Korean families and communities, addiction often carries deep stigma, something to be hidden, endured quietly, or handled within the family rather than spoken about openly. That silence, combined with the difficulty of finding treatment in Korean at all, leaves many people without help. And navigating recovery in English, or through a translator who doesn't share your culture, only adds distance at the moment you most need to be understood.</p>
    <p>You shouldn't have to choose between getting help and being understood. At Regain Hope Detox and Recovery Center, you can do the work of recovery in Korean.</p>
    <p>For a community where treatment in Korean is so rarely available, simply finding a program that can meet you in your language, close to home in Los Angeles, can be the difference between getting help and going without. You shouldn't have to leave your language, or your culture, behind in order to get well.</p>
  </div></section>

  <ImageFeature
    bg="cream"
    image="/images/stock/aftercare.webp"
    alt="A supportive community in recovery"
    side="left"
    eyebrow="Rare and important"
    title="Why care in Korean matters"
    body="Korean-speaking addiction treatment is genuinely hard to find. Most facilities offer, at best, a phone translation line, which can't carry the nuance, trust, or cultural understanding that recovery requires."
    points={[['chat', 'Real Korean-speaking care'], ['family', 'Understanding of cultural stigma'], ['home', "Close to LA's Korean community"]]}
  />

  <section><div class="container rich" style="max-width:820px;">
    <h2>Why Korean-language care is so rare, and so valuable</h2>
    <p>When you can speak openly in Korean and be understood by people who grasp the cultural weight around addiction and family, shame loosens its grip and real healing becomes possible. For Korean individuals and families across Los Angeles, from Koreatown to the Valley, having this option close by is rare and valuable.</p>
    <p>We're careful not to overstate it: care is delivered with genuine Korean-language support within our small, physician-owned program. What you can count on is being able to speak, and be understood, in Korean, without a stranger translating the hardest moments of your life.</p>
    <p>It matters for the family, too. In many Korean households, addiction is something endured in silence, kept from neighbors and even relatives. When the team can speak with the family directly and with cultural understanding, that silence can finally give way to support, which, for many clients, is the turning point. Recovery rarely holds when someone has to hide it from the people closest to them.</p>
  </div></section>

  <section class="bg-cream"><div class="container">
    <div class="sec-head"><span class="eyebrow">The difference</span><h2>Genuine care in Korean</h2></div>
    <div class="grid2" style="max-width:920px;margin:0 auto;">
      {serves.map(([ico, t, d]) => (
        <div class="pcard"><div class="ico"><Icon name={ico} /></div><h3>{t}</h3><p>{d}</p></div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div></section>

  <section><div class="container rich" style="max-width:820px;">
    <h2>Complete care, in Korean</h2>
    <p><a href="/programs/medical-detox/">Medical detox</a>, <a href="/programs/residential-treatment/">residential treatment</a>, <a href="/programs/dual-diagnosis-treatment/">dual-diagnosis care</a>, and <a href="/programs/medication-assisted-treatment/">MAT</a>, with Korean-language support, in a private home with home-cooked meals. The same complete, physician-led continuum, delivered somewhere you can finally be understood.</p>
    <p>And because it's a small, family-run home rather than a large institution, the experience feels personal from the first day: shared meals, unhurried conversation, and a team that remembers who you are. For Korean-speaking clients used to being met with a translation line and a stack of forms, simply being understood in their own language changes everything.</p>
  </div></section>

  <ScenarioHighlight
    bg="cream"
    eyebrow="Be understood, completely"
    title="Recover in a language, and a culture, that understands you"
    intro="Healing is hard enough; it shouldn't be harder because of language or shame. Here you can speak freely in Korean, be understood completely, and recover with dignity, in a home that treats you like family."
    badTitle="What's usually available"
    bad={['At best, a phone translation line', 'Stigma that keeps it hidden', 'Distance at the moment you need understanding']}
    good={['Real Korean-speaking care', 'A team that grasps the cultural weight', "Close to LA's Korean community"]}
    momentLabel="Why it matters"
    scenarios={[
      ['chat', 'When you finally open up', 'Speak freely in Korean and be understood by people who get it.'],
      ['family', 'When family carries shame', 'Met with discretion and compassion for the cultural weight.'],
      ['heart', 'Through the hardest days', 'A small home that treats you like family.'],
    ]}
  />

  <Reviews bg="white" />

  <InsuranceBanner />

  <section><div class="container">
    <div class="sec-head"><span class="eyebrow">FAQ</span><h2>Korean-speaking treatment, frequently asked questions</h2></div>
    <div class="faqwrap">{faqs.map((f, i) => (<details open={i === 0}><summary>{f.q}</summary><p>{f.a}</p></details>))}</div>
  </div></section>

  <section class="ctaband"><div class="container">
    <h2>Recover in a language, and a culture, that understands you</h2>
    <p>One confidential call, 24/7. We'll verify your insurance and guide you with Korean-language support.</p>
    <div class="hero-cta" style="justify-content:center;"><a href="/admissions/verify-insurance/" class="btn btn-gold">Verify Your Insurance</a></div>
  </div></section>
</Layout>
